Reflecting on the state capture inquiry report’s release, ANC Deputy President David Mabuza hailed it as a positive step in the fight against corruption. Mabuza reassured the public that the ANC would continue the fight. But he says it's up to law enforcement to hold those implicated accountable. eNCA's Pule Letshwiti-Jones reports. Courtesy #DStv403 JOHANNESBURG - ANC Deputy President David Mabuza says the release of part one of the state capture inquiry report will not further divide the ruling party. Mabuza says they are prepared, in any event, for the outcome of the final report. READ: State capture whistleblower: It's time to prosecute He was speaking in Limpopo where party leaders met with their traditional and religious counterparts. Mabuza hailed the report as a positive step in the fight against corruption. "It's very important to stand firm on corruption," he said. READ: President Ramaphosa receives state capture inquiry report "Because we can't betray the people who've given their trust to us to look after their resources. "So from time to time we need to strengthen our institutions that are responsible for checking corruption, those institutions must be strengthened and they must work." * eNCA's Pule Letshwiti-Jones reports.